Clintons and Trump's Economic Policy Comparison: It's All About the Money
Both Clinton and Trump want to invest in infrastructure and block the TTP trade deal.
However, the two US presidential candidates disagree on taxation and energy policy, as well as on a fundamental issue.
Underlying the differences in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton is a fundamental, rather philosophical, difference.
The, about the role of the state.
Trump wants to keep those in doubt rather small, warning of how the state can hurt the economy - with taxes and regulations.
Clinton wants to tax the economy to death and regulate it to death, he says.
He himself, however, would be very different, Trump claims.
He will scale back regulations massively, and he is pushing for far-reaching tax reform with lower tax rates - for individuals and businesses.
Clinton, by contrast, says the state has certain tasks to fulfill, has opportunities for the disadvantaged, and needs money to do so.
That's why taxes on the rich would be raised, she says.
Interestingly, the two are very close when it comes to infrastructure.
Trump and Clinton say almost word for word that investment is needed.
The Democratic candidate even announces the biggest investment in new jobs since World War II.
Government infrastructure investment programs are classic Democratic policies, and are strongly opposed by, say, the tea party wing of the Republican Party, which is critical of the government.
So Trump could still face intra-party discussions.
The differences in energy and climate policy are clearer.
Trump wants to build coal-fired power plants and restart coal production in the US.
Oil production should also be possible in previously protected areas; he wants to withdraw from the Paris climate agreement.
Clinton, on the other hand, explicitly wants to expand renewable energies with her investment program, demanding: "One country will become the superpower of clean energy and create millions of jobs."
'It's going to be either China, Germany or America - I want us to be. '
But it's not just infrastructure - the two rivals are not too far apart on international trade agreements, either.
Neither wants to sign the TPP, the Trans-Pacific Trade Agreement.
At the same time, however, both do not want to isolate the US from international trade - they simply want to better protect American jobs.
They should be better paid, Clinton says.
The current minimum wage of $7.25 is a pittance.
She wants to raise it to $15 an hour.
What Trump wants to do on this issue is not entirely clear: at one point he says the minimum wage must go up, then he says it must not be changed.
But the big discussion in the coming months is likely to revolve more around the tax policies of the two camps.
On one side is Trump, who wants to ease the burden on the economy and citizens in order to boost growth.
His critics accuse him of only widening the budget deficit.
On the other side is Clinton, who wants at least the rich to pay more taxes, and whose critics say that raising taxes is not the solution either.
Escape: "Every refugee woman has experience of sexual violence"
Sexual violence is almost a daily occurrence for women fleeing alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatised.
A house offers refuge.
Four women are sitting in a large kitchen.
Each one has a baby who is at most one year old.
One held her young son in her arms.
He gazes curiously into the room with wide eyes.
His mother stares at the tabletop.
Until she realises she's being watched.
She smiles briefly and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until you talk to Katrin Bahr.
She is the Managing Director of Condrobs, a provider of social assistance services in Bavaria, and deals, among other things, with the subject of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralised shelters for single women and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and Münchner Frauenhilfe.
It was recently officially opened.
There are 60 people living there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a security guard at the door.
"It is not an exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has experienced sexual violence while on the run," says Bahr.
"Men flee because of wars, because they are politically persecuted, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as bearers of hope," she says.
For women, other reasons for escaping predominate: "Many steal away secretly because they see no other way out."
In their home countries, they have experienced sexual violence, forced marriages, honour killings, slavery or forced prostitution.
That drives them on.
On the run, it goes on.
"It is not uncommon for smugglers to demand a sexual act for a bottle of water, for example," says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Whoever thinks that this will end as soon as they arrive in Germany is mistaken, says Bahr.
Here too, single women in refugee shelters are often regarded as inferior and, at worst, abused.
As a result, she estimates, about 90 percent of the women living in the accommodation in the north of Munich are traumatized.
'Some of the children certainly didn't come of their own accord. '
Many women are so used to not saying anything.
'Or they don't dare to speak openly about what they've experienced because the shame is too great. '
Since they often do not know how to help themselves, more accommodation is only needed for them, Bahr demands.
In Bavaria, the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees.
When asked whether they were aware of a project similar to the one in Munich in their area of competence, some of them said no.
In Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Even in Swabia, women who have fled alone are not housed separately, says Karl-Heinz Meyer, press spokesman for the government.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower Franconia and Middle Franconia, some dormitories have floors or own houses only for single women and their children.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodations exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
A study published for the committee said: 'It is very important that men and women are housed separately.'
'If there is a lack of privacy or if men and women are housed together, there can be violence against women, which is ongoing. '
Above all, the washrooms should be separate and easily accessible for women, the study says.
The extent to which the women feel this need for protection can be seen from the crush on the house in Munich.
"Since word got around that we exist, we've had a long waiting list," Bahr says.
You could easily open a second house.
