The fact that teenagers and children no longer go outside to play, but rather prefer to spend their free time staring at screens, has been lamented by many over the past decade.
Pokemon Go is about getting people off their couches and becoming more active.
Screen time was initially limited to the TV, then to video games and finally to smartphones.
So it's great to see that technology and outdoor activities are not mutually exclusive.
I am, of course, referring to the Pokémon Go craze, an app based on the characters first created for video games in the 1990s (which later evolved into a cartoon series, playing cards, and other spin-offs).
Like many pop culture phenomena, interest fell slightly before the game's release in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was postponed due to massive demand, which overloaded the servers.
Within days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
How does it work?
In short, players go outside with their smartphones looking for Pokémons that are tracked by GPS and, once found, can be "photographed" (via a screenshot on their phone) or "captured."
A generation who played the game when they were younger joined the craze and leapt off the sofa in search.
In the US, the game has led to a significant increase in the steps the "average" person takes each day.
Cardiogram, an app for Apple Watch that tracks 35,000 users, recently told The Washington Post that within two days of the game's launch, the number of people who exercise for 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent.
The company doesn't know who is playing Pokémon Go - it just sees the raw data to boost performance.
Many public health education campaigns aimed at getting people to "take 30 minutes off," "get off the sofa" and "be active every day" fell on deaf ears, because many public health messages are boring and come from people who look miserable.
Nevertheless, the importance of sport cannot be overstated.
Those who exercise regularly reduce their chances of developing cancer or depression.
Physical activity helps with weight control, high blood pressure, diabetes and a long list of benefits that is too long to list here.
But the wonderful thing about Pokémon Go is that it gets people to do something outdoors that they enjoy.
This covers three pillars of health - exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends while hunting.
As ever, there are grumpy old game changers who have to complain about something.
And yes, someone could run against a door.
What's the point?
There has been a breakthrough.
Even though smartphone apps like Fitbit have been able to track our activity in the past, they haven't given us any reason to exercise like this game does.
The new will lose its allure and use will diminish over time.
However, because of Pokemon's success, there will be more games that combine apps and virtual reality with real-world activity, helping many people in the hunt to be more active, fitter and healthier.
