Community, Mind, Health: Singing is good for seniors
Singing has accompanied Ursel Kipp all her life: as a young girl she was in the school choir, she studied music as a teacher, and today the 78-year-old sings in a senior choir.
"Singing moves me - emotionally and physically," she says.
After rehearsals, she says, she feels balanced, cheerful and overall more alive.
She is doing something good for her health and her mind.
Singing is a great hobby for seniors from several perspectives, says Erhard Hackler from the German Senior League.
Most seniors sing in a choir and share the joy of music with like-minded people, describes Hackler.
By regularly being together seniors can socialize and maintain social contacts.
This is because social and family structures often dissolve in old age, and a choir is then an ideal opportunity to spend time with other people.
Ursel Kipp also experienced this in her choir: "To coordinate and organize, to be able to rely on others and to learn from each other - a choir is a very special form of being together."
Singing can be exhausting in a positive sense, says Hackler.
This is because seniors train deep and controlled breathing.
Those who regularly demand their lungs do not get out of breath so quickly, even in everyday life.
Even when it comes to preserving the sound of the voice in old age, singing is an ideal hobby.
Singing often has a very special effect on older people, says Ursula Lenz from the Federal Association of Senior Citizens "Organisations.
In the older generations singing together was much more important, it was part of everyday life, both at school and in leisure time, she explains.
Lenz often observes that singing or listening to songs awakens many memories in older people, often associated with positive feelings from their youth.
Through lyrics and especially melodies, even people suffering from dementia remember events from a long time ago.
When singing, the head is also required to perform particularly well, explains Lenz.
Concentrating on one's own voice and a given rhythm at the same time and adapting to the other singers - this is a great cognitive challenge.
Especially older people, who live alone, practice not only to concentrate on themselves.
Another positive aspect is the recognition you get from singing in a choir, says Hackler.
An enthusiastic audience is a great compliment.
Self-esteem also grows through singing in a choir.
To show oneself: when I practice for a long time, I get better and grow beyond myself - this experience strengthens me.
So there are plenty of good reasons to start singing.
If you want to try out a new hobby, don't hesitate - even if you think you have little talent, advises Lenz.
You don't sing alone - with 50 people singing, who hears when a note goes wrong?
In search of the right offer, seniors have different options, says Hackler.
If someone from your circle of acquaintances sings in a seniors "choir, you can simply join in.
Many towns also offer overviews of the choirs in the area.
Anyone wishing to sing in a church choir can contact the congregation or the church leader directly.
Many senior choirs can also be found on the Internet.
If you don't have access to the internet, you can ask your family, friends or neighbours for help with your internet search.
If you want to sing, you should definitely join a choir, advises Hackler.
Singing is good for the soul and has something liberating - this applies to all ages.
Cats react more sensitively than cats to the cries of the kittens
Biologists in Hanover have investigated the effect of calling cat babies on adult animals.
To their surprise, the meowing did not leave the males indifferent either - however, in contrast to the females, they always behaved the same way.
Female cats can recognize the arousal of kittens by the meowing of the kittens.
They react ten percent faster to sounds from kittens who think they are in great need, as scientists from the University of Veterinary Medicine and the Hannover Medical School (MHH) have discovered.
Hangovers also react to the calls of kittens - but always in the same way.
"Apparently, the acoustic differences between the meowing of less and more excitable juveniles are either imperceptible or of no importance to the males," said biologist Wiebke Konerding from the MHH.
She is the lead author of the study, which was published this Friday in the journal BMC Evolutionary Biology.
In a previous study, the research team had already found that the duration and pitch of kitten cries varied with the urgency of their need for help.
A total of nine adult males and eight females from MHH livestock farming were observed.
On the one hand, they were played calls from little ones who were taken out of the litter box for three minutes and separated from their mother and siblings.
On the other hand they were confronted with cries of more excited kittens, which were lifted up additionally.
Despite the small sample size, the researchers consider their results to be significant.
"All females, even those that did not yet have offspring of their own, reacted differentiated to the cries," Konerding said.
They turned to the loudspeaker more quickly when it played the calls of the more excited kittens.
This ability is possibly innate or develops with sexual maturity.
"One surprise was that the males reacted at all," the biologist said.
In the past, scientists have repeatedly studied the reactions of women and men to baby sounds in humans.
Some studies also showed that women reacted more sensitively to infants, regardless of whether they were already mothers or not, reported biologist Marina Scheumann.
