Military leaders falsified ISIS intelligence, Congressional committee finds
Military officials from the United States Central Command altered intelligence to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the so-called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, a congressional committee of inquiry said in a report on Thursday.
The preliminary report, prepared by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Services Committee, Intelligence Committee, and the Defense Budget Committee, reported deep dissatisfaction among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors were changing their assessments of America's efforts to fight the Islamic State.
Central Command, or Cencom for short, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, which oversees American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence that was typically nodded off by senior Centcom commanders regularly painted a more positive picture of America's counter-terrorism efforts than actual conditions on the ground would have permitted, and was consistently more positive than analysis by other intelligence agencies," a newspaper article quoted the report as saying.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analysis is presented to our political leaders," said Ken Calvert, a Republican member of the House of Representatives.
The leadership failures at Centcom extend to the very top of the organisation.
The 10-page report details persistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analyses of American efforts to train Iraqi forces.
While it provides no direct evidence that Obama administration leaders have given instructions to alter the reports, it shows how analysts have faced pressure from their superiors to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat posed by the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and testimony to Congress were significantly more positive than is true," the report noted.
For example, a Centcom official announced publicly that a military recapture of Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
"After months of investigation, this much is clear," Mike Pompeo, a Republican congressman from Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, Central Command leaders altered intelligence reports to downplay the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans created the task force after it was leaked that analysts were concerned about the manipulation of Islamic State reports.
The report, released on Thursday, will be completed with more detailed findings as the investigation continues.
In addition, further investigations of Centcom reports by the Department of Defense inspector general are ongoing.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday that agreed with some of the conclusions of the Republican task force.
"In 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly constrained process for producing intelligence assessments on ISIL and the Iraqi security services," the committee's top Democrat, House member Adam B. Schiff, said in a statement.
That process, Mr. Schiff said, "delayed the release of intelligence reports," damaged morale among analysts and "left unduly little room for dissent."
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats said they found no evidence of White House interference with Centcom analysts regarding a "particular political opinion."
The preliminary results of the congressional investigation were released Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, the New York Times reported an investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general, which was launched after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on congressional reports while the inspector general's investigation was ongoing.
But he also noted that "experts sometimes have very divergent opinions on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a controversial discussion of these important national defense issues."
The investigation has repercussions beyond the question of a successful American-led air campaign in Iraq and Syria (a claim now being made by a growing number of Defense Department officials).
Last year's allegations, however, have raised questions about the extent to which President Obama can rely on Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya, and other crisis regions.
Criticism of classified information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of more than a decade ago, when a Centcom analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote about how, against the advice of many analysts, the then-George W. Bush administration envisaged only a small occupation force in Iraq and spent little time worrying about the aftermath of the 2003 invasion.
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against current Islamic State coverage.
Last year, according to government officials, Mr. Hooker's team concluded that, contrary to what the government had said, airstrikes against Islamic State-held refineries would not have a significant impact on the terrorist group's financial position, as they would have used makeshift refineries to sell oil on the black market.
That finding, however, was not made public, The Times reported in September.
Centcom's then-commander, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized by lawmakers for his overly positive assessment of the war situation at a Senate hearing.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced at Central Command by Gen. Joseph L. Votel.
