Amid the Rage of the Olympics, the Zen of Trampoline
Wherever you are, however late it is, it is the Olympics.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inescapable, a frantic relay between competition and aspiration.
It is as if the Olympic torch itself were a burning baton, passed from crossbowman to swimmer to gymnast to triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read a newspaper or listen to your neighbor talk in the coffee shop queue without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky or the argument between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, entering the Olympics for the first time and a swarm of women with dimples, could easily have been one of those household names broadcast in prime time, built up through sponsors and feel-good TV commercials, if he were a swimmer, gymnast or even fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is competing for gold in Olympic trampoline gymnastics.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate every event the same way.
Further from the centre, partly in the shade, are the non-universally recognised sports: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We will always have the breaststroke and long may it reign.
But if I may modestly make the case for my particular favourite, let me draw attention to the discreet charm of the trampoline.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic event since 2000, when it made its debut in Sydney, it has been so poorly perceived for the last 16 years that many of those I interviewed did not know it was an Olympic sport at all.
This could also be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to compete, it has never won a medal in trampoline jumping, and until 2012 had one athlete who made it to the final round.
The Chinese and the Russians tend to share the prices for the men and the Chinese and the Canadians the prices for the women.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie MacLennan of Canada will defend their gold medals from London this year.
Trampoline jumping has a certain outsider charm, partly because to the unenlightened ear it sounds more appropriate for a clown school than for the Olympic Games.
At this point, I should admit that I am not an expert, but only a down-to-earth enthusiast.
It has humorous potential - the cartoonish tremor of its never-ending impact - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports that essentially unite it.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish El Trampoline, which means "springboard."
Aspiring winners jump on a gigantic trampoline, shoot up to 30 feet in the air and have to perform a series of falling movements (spins, pike and somersaults) before landing on their feet.
According to the official Olympic programme, they are evaluated according to their execution, degree of difficulty and "flight time."
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic vector is straight.
Medal hopefuls must go further, faster, up and over in their pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish, sometimes back and forth, up and down the playground.
They are not only chasing the finish line or the exit wall, but also another mocking target on television: the world or Olympic record.
The single-minded pursuit is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and it is enough to move even a spectator to tears.
But it's also what I find a little tiring, even watching these games.
The trampoline offers a reprieve from this.
The vector of the trampoline jumper is above.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she bounces off, seemingly weightless like an astronaut, going up, then down, then back up effortlessly.
Here, too, there is competition, not without difficulty, of course, but during the exercise there is no frantic attack on the target, no arching into the distance, only the dreamy, elegant suspension of time and gravity.
It's as Zen as competing in the Olympics can be.
The women's qualifying and final will take place on Friday afternoon, streaming at 1pm Eastern Time; the men's final on Saturday, also at 1pm.
NBC will air the finals as part of an afternoon block on both days starting at 2 p.m.
Amid the Olympic mania, they promise a quiet, nice moment, one that is likely to be overlooked in the general uproar.
If raising awareness can only be achieved by gasping and objectifying male athletes - as male US gymnasts recently suggested, according to The Wall Street Journal - then Mr Dooley can expect his new fan base to be gasping for air.
"A Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, Long a U.S. Ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators calling for political change in Ethiopia met with violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were killed in gun battles during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
For the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable countries, a solid Western ally with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country and spread to more and more areas.
Last week, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
The government's response was ruthless, according to human rights groups.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Videos circulating of the protests, believed to be from last year or early this year, show security guards beating young people with sticks as they were forced to do a handstand against a wall.
The head of the UN human rights agency is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together, and it will be even harder in the future," said Rashid Abdi, the Horn of Africa project manager for the International Crisis Group, a research group.
After Nigeria, Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa and its stability is valued by the West.
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats beyond the region, especially in Somalia. Few countries in Africa, if any, receive as much Western aid.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a remarkable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
The streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
While Ethiopia has been far from a model of democracy - human rights organizations have consistently cited government repression - the country's opposition has been curtailed, effectively silencing dissidents.
Many were sent into exile or prison, killed or driven into the wilderness.
But that could change.
"If you oppress people and they have no other options but to protest, it breaks out," said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
A generation protests.
There are numerous complaints covering everything from land use to a stranglehold on the ruling coalition's power.
After a widely criticized election last year, the ruling party and its allies won the opposition's last seat and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea; a battle over the jagged, disputed line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, could take advantage of the turmoil and rearm.
Several factors explain why, after years of simmering beneath the surface, feelings of resentment are now exploding.
The first seems innocuous: smartphones.
Only in recent years have many Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media, as cheaper smartphones have become more common and Internet services have improved.
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, as it does periodically, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through Internet proxies that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered to protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
For eons, the Amharas, who hail from Ethopia's predominantly Christian highlands, have prospered in politics and economics while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslim and live in lowland areas.
But that, too, is changing.
"We are coordinating under one umbrella," said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromos leader.
The largest protests took place in areas of Amhara and Oromos.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, who make up about 6% of the population and are dominant in the military, intelligence, commerce, and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death from an undisclosed illness in 2012.
He was regarded as a tactical genius, a man who could think around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at spotting early signs of dissatisfaction and using special envoys to process opponents and neutralize them.
"The current regime lacks that basic skill," said Mr. Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was chosen to replace Mr Meles for relatively obscure reasons.
Unlike Mr. Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr. Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of the Tigris-controlled security services.
Many fear the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such turmoil was in 2005, when thousands protested against elections that analysts said appeared to have been botched by the government and subsequently stolen.
During the ensuing raids, many protesters were killed, though fewer than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for measurable progress in poverty reduction.
But obviously this has not prevented the intensification of the Ethiopian government's internal resentment.
And it is taking on a dangerous ethnic shape.
Last month, protesters attacked shops run by Tigray in Gondar, an Amharic city, and hatred of the Tigray is becoming increasingly common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies in a strange position.
The American government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it had closed that base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it does not want its ally to collapse in an already volatile region.
"This," Mr. Abdi said, "is a very thin line."
