"Rich foods were very popular," Ziegelman said.
There was peanut bread, liver cheese and bean bread.
They were made from one ingredient and something cheap that stretches the ingredient.
Imagine eating so many peanuts that they serve as dinner.
Coe grinned.
"It must have settled in my stomach like lead," he said.
In the years before the Great Depression, the table in an American household, especially in rural areas, was an all-you-can-eat buffet.
Teams of women cooked for male field workers and freshly baked pies were served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. "A Square Meal" chronicles the ways in which the country coped with no longer being the land of larvae.
"It was a time when food became a central, tense issue for Americans," Coe said, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
The new budget diet was just as fraught: Mysterious foods like breads and casseroles became staples, and the casserole dish was a "wonderful way to recycle leftovers," Ziegelman noted, because chefs could hide unappetizing ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit has been replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, which for years was the center of American cuisine, has become a rarely served luxury.
Strange mixtures were tried, as calorific and nutritious satisfaction took precedence over taste or even common sense.
During her research for the book, which also includes recipes, Ziegelman prepared a dish from that era, baked onions with peanut butter.
"It wasn't a popular addition at lunchtime," says Coe.
Ziegelmann continued: 'It was surreal.'
Peanut butter and baked onions don't match.
It was typical of many of the household recipes.
Household economists - including Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - drove the country's eating habits like never before or since.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged women to become "household policymakers" and rise to the challenge of turning pimps into delicious meals, like creamy spaghetti with carrots.
"A Square Meal" is a feast of historical delicacies.
Particularly palatable are the accounts of the government's response to starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's let-me-eat-cake attitude.
While publicly praising the simple Iowa farmhouse cuisine of his kitchen, he dined like the multi-millionaire man of the world he has become.
"He liked continental cuisine like fish with cucumber sauce," Coe said.
He ate in an almost gilded dining room and wore a tuxedo.
He was gloriously out of touch.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not asked him to set an example with his stomach.
As described in the book, Mrs. Roosevelt's hiring of a housekeeper with no interest in flavors resulted in the White House producing the most boring food in Washington, but also one of the most desolate. "
Many of the Great Depression-era ways of dealing with food were discarded as soon as the country got back on its feet.
The legacy lies in our continued focus on calories and food, Ziegelman said, as well as how science has been applied to food.
When writing the book, the couple said they had a better understanding of Ziegelman's mother-in-law's eating habits - such as how she couldn't throw away food.
"She had a real fear of food waste," Coe said.
Ziegelman recalled, "It actually made people sick."
There was the windbag incident.
After the plates were cleared at Eisenberg's, she and Coe pulled out a dessert they had prepared at home: the plum dessert that President Roosevelt ate for lunch.
