Greenland shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
Rare sight.
Greenland sharks usually only come to the surface in winter.
This shark was allowed to return to the sea after an investigation on board the research vessel Sanna.
He was born in 1624 and swims with a good 1 km / h through the North Atlantic - until today.
Greenland sharks don't produce offspring until they are 150 years old.
The Greenland shark swims leisurely along the bottom of the North Atlantic, reaching an average distance of 1,220 metres in an hour.
Only when it matters, the five-metre-long animal accelerates to a whopping 2.6 km / h - and at this top speed is half as fast as a seal.
However, this slowness of life seems to be a silver bullet for old age.
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal Science about a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old.
"Madness," says Alexander Scheuerlein from the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock, commenting on this lifespan, which represents a world record for vertebrates.
The evolutionary biologist has long suspected that Greenland sharks are getting rock-old.
The only thing missing was the evidence.
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe, as they live mainly in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Spitsbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures of around six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in winter.
Accordingly, researchers know little about the lifestyles of Greenland sharks.
They measured their slow motion speed when they equipped six animals with a transmitter off Svalbard.
These sharks still prey: Researchers found the remains of a seal in an animal's stomach, while another had swallowed the jaw bone of a young polar bear.
Possibly they hunt sleeping animals or patrol at the bottom of the ice-sea and look for carcasses, that stagger down from higher water-layers.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues studied 28 Greenland sharks caught by fishermen from the depths of the North Atlantic off Greenland or Svalbard between 2010 and 2013.
The smallest shark was just 81 centimetres long, while the largest measured 502 centimetres.
To determine the age of the sharks, they used the carbon-14 method to analyze the lens core of the sharks.
This center of the eye lens arises even before the birth of the sharks, the proteins contained therein are not renewed later.
The two smallest sharks had remarkably high levels of carbon-14 in the lens core.
They were therefore born after the early 1960 "s, when nuclear weapons tests dumped large quantities of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
In contrast, the lens core of the third smallest animal, 220 centimetres long, contained a small surplus of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons tests, so it must have celebrated its 50th birthday when it was examined in 2012.
All larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had normal amounts of carbon 14 in their lens core, which is produced by cosmic rays in the atmosphere.
In fact, the carbon 14 clock showed an age of 335 years for a 493-centimetre Greenland shark, while the record-breaking shark, at 502 centimetres, is likely to be 392 years old.
It was known that female Greenland sharks only produce offspring when they are longer than four metres.
The researchers were now able to assign an age to the length.
Since one of the animals, measuring 392 centimetres, was probably on the threshold of sexual maturity and its age was determined at 156 years, Greenland sharks apparently take at least a century and a half to reproduce.
That, too, is likely to be a world record for vertebrates at the moment.
That such methusalems live primarily in icy waters is no coincidence.
The previous record holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale with a 120-year-old harpoon tip stuck in its neck, was also caught off Alaska.
Due to the low temperatures, the organism of the animals living there often runs on a low flame.
They mature later - and age more slowly.
In order to keep themselves warm in cold water, the animals often grow particularly large.
This is because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
The heat loss of one gram of mouse is therefore much greater than that of one gram of elephant.
Another advantage: you have fewer enemies.
"A smaller animal lives more dangerously and should concentrate on having as many offspring as possible as early as possible," explains Scheuerlein, an evolutionary biologist.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should invest its resources in a long life.
