Nokia 9000 Communicator: The first smartphone
E-mail and the Internet in slow motion: 20 years ago the Nokia Communicator came onto the market.
Its successors now dominate the world - its manufacturer suffered a disaster.
The device weighed almost half a kilogram and was more than four times as heavy as an iPhone 5.
It was thicker and bigger, so it didn't sit well in your hand.
On the contrary, it was pretty clunky.
The built-in memory was initially eight megabytes, which would be enough for about two high-resolution selfies today.
An iPhone now ships with at least 16 gigabytes.
The Nokia 9000 Communicator went on sale exactly 20 years ago, on 15 August 1996 - and it was the first smartphone.
For a few euros, lovers can still buy the devices on the Internet, but they somehow date back to the Stone Age of the Internet age.
Twenty years ago, however, the Communicator was a sensation.
The Finnish mobile phone manufacturer had announced the product as a "pocket-sized office" a few months earlier at the Cebit computer fair in Hanover.
In fact, the new mobile phone could do a lot for the standards of the time: SMS and e-mails could be sent and received, and the communicator could also be reached by fax.
Even access to websites was possible via HTML browser, albeit painfully slow.
A calculator was available, a digital address book and an electronic calendar.
There was a small antenna, and the phone could be opened like a laptop.
Then there was a small keyboard and a black-and-white screen.
Pretty proud was the price: 2700 D-Mark, about 1400 Euro.
The average selling price of a smartphone in Germany in 2015 was 392 euros.
Nobody could have guessed in August 1996 that the Communicator would be the beginning of the smartphone era.
Everything has changed since then.
The smart phones are a success story, though not for Nokia.
The mobile phone division of the Finns experienced an unprecedented disaster, was eventually sold to Microsoft and wound up.
Today, the market is dominated by providers, all of whom came much later than Nokia.
Being online anytime and anywhere is a daily routine for many people today.
In 2015, there were nearly two billion smartphone users worldwide.
About 1.4 billion devices were sold, of which Samsung and Apple alone account for 555 million units.
Worldwide sales of the devices amount to around 400 billion euros.
Add to that the well-run businesses of countless app providers and telecommunications companies.
In the meantime, an entire industry has emerged around smartphones.
The decisive breakthrough to the mass market came only at the beginning of 2007, when Apple CEO Steve Jobs announced the introduction of the iPhone at Mac World.
He promised three devices in one: a music player, a telephone and an Internet communicator, all easy to use via touch screen.
Apple's triumphant march began, and the iPhone is still the company's most important product today.
Nokia, Motorola and Blackberry, which dominated the market, were lagging behind.
They eventually disappeared, and Blackberry has struggled.
Apple and Asian suppliers such as Samsung now call the shots.
Twenty years after its invention, the smartphone is a matter of course.
On average, every German now looks at his mobile phone 88 times a day.
"We all have to learn to put our smartphones away," said Janina Kugel, who is responsible for human resources on the Siemens Executive Board.
Permanent accessibility has become both a curse and a blessing.
