Data theft: How perfidious hackers extort their ransom
Programmers of extortion malware are currently targeting companies - and succeeding in doing so.
According to a recent survey of 540 companies in North America, Great Britain and Germany by Malwarebytes, the malware defense specialists, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been the victims of an attack with extortion software at least once in the past twelve months, sometimes several times.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have already been the target of ransomware extortion.
40 percent of the victims willingly paid the ransoms demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to use the attacked systems and data again.
According to the observations of Malwarebytes, the perpetrators increasingly specialize their extortion software in attacks on corporate networks.
If they are successful there, the potential ransom to be extorted will be significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently witnessing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with "Welt."
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send advertisements.
Then the perpetrators discovered extortion software for themselves.
At first, private users were the target, but the switch to corporate attacks has been alarmingly rapid in recent months.
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern: Once active on a victim's computer, it specifically searches for recently modified files such as Word, Excel or database files, as well as archives of pictures and videos.
The Ransomware encrypts these files and permanently deletes the originals.
The software then presents the extortioners "demands.
In order to get the encryption code to the files, victims must transfer money - usually in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project databases, without which production stops.
Accordingly, the damage is higher if a Ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported losses in turnover due to Ransomware, 13 percent even had to interrupt business completely, in one case people were in danger of their lives.
In Germany, several hospitals have already been the victims of attacks, whose patients can be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always say to the victims: don't pay, you are only promoting the problem," Kleczynski explains.
But 80 to 90 percent of the companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to dismiss the offender's claim when the operation is at a standstill.
The hackers, on the other hand, know this and try everything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, the security researchers at F-Secure examined the user interfaces and contact with the extortioners and come to the conclusion that the perpetrators are actually trying to set up a kind of customer service in order to earn more money.
They chat to their victims about how to pay with Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites or decrypt sample files for free.
And if private individuals are released after payments of a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-figure sums in order to get their data back unencrypted.
In view of the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware extortion, the hackers are becoming more professional and share the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of the antivirus provider Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware within about a week."
However, it is more likely that it is three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software kit to the actual extortioners.
The previous malware kits were created by buying the malware itself, advice and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price of between $1000 and $10,000.
"A customization tool is included so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," Wisniewski says.
The blackmailers then look for more hackers to distribute the freshly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from a criminal and commission another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"Usually, criminals then hire spammers to spread it," Wisniewski explains.
The risk of ransomware is now known at many companies that back up their data better.
Over 50 percent of the company IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to fend off ransomware by means of file back-ups and scanner software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If data encryption alone is no longer a sufficient threat for successful extortion, the perpetrators instead threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
Depending on the type of data, the damage potential is thus many times higher than before.
In the future, the perpetrators could also target completely new targets on the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could gain control of a thermostat connected to the Internet.
In the middle of winter, unlocking such a blocked heating system could well be worth a ransom for some victims.
If the perpetrators then block an entire production line in a factory instead of the heating in the future, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
