Relaxing night: Tips against sleep disorders
In the evening you roll around forever, at night you lie awake for hours, in the morning you can't think about sleep even long before the alarm rings.
This is anything but relaxing.
After all, one is in good company with such problems: According to the Robert Koch Institute, about a quarter of adults have sleep disorders and more than ten percent often or permanently experience their sleep as not restorative.
How do sleep problems or sleep disorders manifest themselves?
There are several forms of sleep disorders, and there can be a variety of underlying causes, emphasizes Hans-Günter Weeß, board member of the German Society for Sleep Research and Sleep Medicine.
However, what is commonly understood by this is insomnia, i.e. a disturbance of falling asleep and falling asleep.
Many people find sleeping through particularly unsatisfactory or insufficient, says Jens Wagenknecht, board member of the German General Practitioners Association with practice in Varel in Lower Saxony.
What is behind sleep disorders?
The causes of sleep disorders are complex.
This can be due to organic, psychological or behavioural factors, as well as medication.
It is not uncommon for a sleep disorder to be an expression of another disease.
"Very early waking is common, especially with depression," Weeß says.
And it may be that different factors cause each other.
For example, someone who has a herniated disc can lie down badly, wakes up every two to three hours and possibly begins to ponder everyday problems and worries, Weeß gives an example.
This leads to tension and sleep is no longer possible.
When should I go to the doctor with insomnia?
Anyone who does not sleep well for at least three nights a week for a period of one month and is impaired during the day should see a doctor, advises Weeß.
The impairment can look very different: one is exhausted, tired, unrested, has difficulties with attention and concentration, is easily irritable, has mood swings or physical complaints such as stomach or headaches.
In order to alleviate the sleep disorder, it is important to find out its causes.
Treatment options include behavioural changes, cognitive behavioural therapy or medication - classic sleeping pills only in exceptional cases and for a maximum of two weeks.
Professor Ingo Fietze, Head of the Interdisciplinary Sleep Medicine Centre at the Charité Universitätsmedizin Berlin, emphasises that there are hardly any established sleep physicians in Germany.
Therefore, if you have problems sleeping, you should first consult your GP, advises Weeß.
This can clarify with investigations whether the problems have a physical cause.
Who should go to the sleep laboratory, and what happens?
Doctors advise examining in the sleep laboratory, for example, in case of snoring with breathing interruptions, in case of pathological daytime tiredness, in case of sleepwalkers or if the cause of a sleep disturbance is not found, Fietze explains.
You don't really have to prepare for the examination.
You should spend the day as normal.
"Just don't take an afternoon nap, please," Fietze says.
After wiring, you go to bed at your normal time.
In addition to the electrodes on the body, you wear nasal glasses, a chest strap and a sensor on your finger.
In addition, a camera on the ceiling records the sleeping person.
How can sufferers get to grips with the problems?
There are quite a few adjustments you can make for a better night's sleep.
Weeß enumerates: regular bedtimes and getting up times, not lying in bed too long, not sleeping during the day, not watching TV to fall asleep, avoiding alcohol and not looking at the clock at night - then you start counting immediately, and that is not beneficial at all.
