Friedrichshain in the east of Berlin was actually a traditional working-class district, which still has a low average income and a high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city.
Squats and the housing projects born of them have also long been part of the neighbourhood: in 1990, numerous houses in the former GDR were occupied, including almost the entire Mainzer Strasse very close to the Rigaer.
While the people of Mainz were evicted in a real street battle under a large police presence, many of the projects in Riga were legalized and are still inhabited by the people who occupied them 26 years ago.
At the same time, the district has increasingly become a magnet for tourists and Berliners from all over the world in recent years: residents from GDR times and former squatters now share their neighbourhoods with them.
This is also reflected in rents, which have risen by almost 60 per cent since 2009 on new rentals.
Many of the new buildings in Riga are being attacked as symbols of this development: they can be recognised by discarded windows or freshly painted facades that have been pelted with paint bags.
No other street has been mentioned so often this year along with the words "left-wing violence."
One reason that not all neighbors see this as a problem may be that they are not necessarily affected by crime: according to statistics, crimes such as assault are almost exclusively committed against police officers.
The majority of crimes are property damage, which tends to hit new buildings and newly renovated houses more.
For Kerstin Neugebauer, who has lived in a rented house next to the controversial 94 for 17 years, there can be no question of uncertainty.
As far as violence is concerned, it's reassuring: the people in 94 are their neighbors, and they certainly weren't.
Even the famous burning cars have not been around in Riga for some time.
For the trained architect, her street is not a criminal focal point, on the contrary: "Here you help each other, live together on the street and get more out of each other than anywhere else."
Neugebauer deliberately moved to Rigaer Strasse - and stayed there.
That is why it was so important to her that the residents get their street back: from the police, the politicians and the media, who all suddenly claimed sovereignty of interpretation over the district in July.
But in the eyes of residents like Neugebauer, the street continues to be taken away from them: through faceless new buildings in former vacant lots that displace the old residents.
"At the end of the day, these are condominiums that are not of interest to a lot of people here - they tend to be people who are not so well-heeled," she says.
'I absolutely don't condone violence and destruction. '
But what should you do if no one ever listens to you?
There is frustration on all sides, including the police and residents.
Kerstin Neugebauer has little sympathy for newcomers who are annoyed by paint bombs: the house projects and the left scene belonged to the neighbourhood.
Anyone who moves here should be aware of this - just as someone who moves to a pub area can't complain about noise there.
