Urbach: Annika Deuschle is the new Refugee Commissioner
Annika Deuschle is the contact person for integration and organisation.
She is also a local social worker.
Annika Deuschle has been the Refugee Commissioner for Urbach since July.
The social pedagogue supports the administration team headed by Achim Grockenberger.
She sees herself as a point of contact for all stakeholders: refugees, the Refugee Aid Working Group, administration, authorities and anyone else involved.
Regine Kunde from the working group indicates that the volunteers are more than grateful that Deuschle is now here, the egg-laying woolly sow who has one problem above all else.
This is what some had said - not so much mocking as aiming at the multitude of desirable tasks - when the administration wanted to advertise the job.
We were looking for an administrative specialist with a talent for languages and people, combined with many years of experience in the field of social work, namely an egg-laying woolly mouse.
But administrative work is not her central area, says Annika Deuschle.
Above all it is about organization, work with the people on site and also behind the scenes as well as networking.
The 31-year-old has been with the club for around six weeks.
She has a 50 per cent job for a three-year term.
"It was high time," says Regine Kunde, that Annika Deuschle supported honorary and full-time actors.
There are big and small problems, organisational, human and communication problems.
New containers will soon be available in Wasenstrasse
Finding accommodation for the refugees who have been recognised has been a serious problem for some time.
The municipalities are responsible for the connecting accommodation.
They must accommodate the refugees in their own or rented accommodation.
The costs of building, renting or renovating these accommodation must be borne by the municipalities themselves.
Responsibility changes from the district administration office to the municipality and job centre.
Problem: There are available properties, but not every landlord wants to offer his flat.
The search has been very difficult for some time.
De facto, the administration does not find private housing.
So far, it has not worked, relying on private dwellings, Deuschle said.
Therefore, communal housing must be upgraded, as the saying goes.
So new containers will soon be erected in Wasenstrasse.
But only apartments are not enough.
Perspective is the key word, Regine Kunde and Annika Deuschle agree.
In addition to permanent residence, there are traineeships, apprenticeships, school places, one-euro jobs and temporary jobs for refugees and migrants that have to be found or established.
"More seats would be good," Regine Kunde reports.
Many work in the building yard or help caretakers, do community service - and this is motivated and very tidy, as Annika Deuschle reports.
She hopes the work will have a positive impact on the community.
This is "not occupational therapy."
Activity does not just mean work.
The day needs a fixed structure, Deuschle and his customers say.
People need to develop a sense of belonging.
Therefore, there is a need for offers such as sports, contacts with locals and, above all, language courses.
Professional courses are rare.
So administration and volunteers are also stepping in.
It is crucial that the refugees get the feeling that they are wanted and welcome in Germany.
The long duration of the proceedings was a problem.
They have to explain to the refugees that it is taking time and that they can bridge the time sensibly, for example with language courses.
Anyone who at some point develops the feeling that he cannot help anyone in Urbach, is not allowed to work and is useless, will never integrate.
The clear majority is motivated.
But there are also problem cases, says Kunde honestly, "people for whom nothing is possible." The work of Deuschle and Kunde is therefore always also to motivate others.
It was all a "mammoth task," he said.
A difficult question: After recent events, are they afraid of radicalisation, even in a small community like Urbach?
"No," Regine Kunde says quite clearly, "which some might call naive." However, she cannot and does not want to rule out residual risk.
But the helpers are already aware of this.
These incidents are also an issue for the refugees.
They are afraid that the attackers will bring them into complete disrepute.
"They want to show that they have nothing to do with it," says Regine Kunde.
Many would like to stay in Urbach.
So senior and volunteer staff on the ground and in the region need to look for work.
They always keep in mind that a new influx of refugees and migrants could soon arrive in Urbach.
Does Germany need a cap?
Politicians shy away from answering this question clearly.
Actually, it's unfair to put them on the spot.
"In Urbach we have not yet arrived where we would like to go," says Annika Deuschle.
No new refugees, that would ease the situation.
Regine Kunde also makes it clear that the people of Urbach are already busy integrating the existing people in a sensible way.
There are currently around 100 people, mostly young men.
But when people are in need, they have to be helped, both women agree.
The political situation in the world is so complicated that there are no easy answers.
Schorndorf: Burglar with helicopter wanted
